            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dr. Simone Jones carries the ingrained belief that every system, from a family to a Fortune 500 company, can be made healthier. This conviction was forged in her childhood home in Detroit, where her father, a proud UAW autoworker, and her mother, a public school teacher, debated the mechanics of unions and classrooms around the dinner table. They instilled in her a respect for structure and a deep empathy for the people within it.\n\nHer academic path was a straight line driven by this fascination. An undergraduate degree at the University of Michigan led her west to UC Berkeley for her PhD in Organizational Psychology, where she fell in love with the Bay Area\u2019s blend of intellectual rigor and cultural dynamism. Her early career was spent in-house, helping tech companies navigate the growing pains of rapid scaling. A key turning point came during her mid-30s; a challenging divorce forced her to apply her professional principles to her own life, rebuilding her personal \"organization\" with intention and resilience.\n\nThis experience crystallized her ambition. She left the corporate world and joined a prestigious consulting firm, quickly rising to Principal. Today, Simone is the person CEOs call when their company culture is broken. Her days are a mix of high-stakes workshops in sleek Financial District boardrooms and deep-dive data analysis.\n\nHer life is rooted in her Hayes Valley apartment, a sanctuary of calm filled with books and art from local makers. Her 3.8-mile commute on the Muni is a cherished ritual\u2014a time for observing the city\u2019s complex human ecosystem or listening to a podcast. Evenings are for her chosen family: a tight-knit group of friends, many of them fellow transplants, who gather for dinners, gallery openings, or performances at the nearby SFJAZZ Center.\n\nAt 48, Simone feels a sense of grounded accomplishment. Her current dream is to synthesize her experience into a book on creating resilient and equitable workplaces. San Francisco, for her, is more than a city; it\u2019s the perfect laboratory and home, a place that continually challenges her intellect and nourishes her soul."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers the feeling of the cool stone steps of Sproul Hall, late one night during her PhD. The Berkeley air was electric with debate and possibility. She\u2019d just left a heated study group, her mind buzzing not with theory, but with the human dynamics behind the data. That night, she didn\u2019t just feel smart; she felt seen. It was the moment California stopped being a place she studied and became the place she belonged. This intellectual homecoming cemented her future on the West Coast, sealing a bond with the Bay Area's vibrant spirit.\n\n2.\nShe remembers the silence after the last box from her marriage was gone. Sitting on the floor of her Hayes Valley apartment, surrounded by echoes, she felt a terrifying clarity. Her personal \u201corganization\u201d had collapsed. For the first time, she had to apply her principles not to a client, but to herself. That quiet, painful moment in her mid-30s wasn't an ending; it was the raw, foundational work of rebuilding her own system from the ground up. It was the birth of her true resilience and the beginning of her real work.\n\n3.\nIt was in a sterile downtown boardroom, two years into her consulting career. The tech CEO, a known cynic, had his arms crossed for hours. Then, during a fraught exercise on trust, something Simone said clicked. He put his hands on the table, leaned forward, and said, \"Okay. I get it now.\" The shift was tectonic. For Simone, it was more than a win; it was profound validation. It was proof that leaving her old life to fix broken systems from the outside was not just a job, but her calling.\n\n4.\nShe recalls arriving home in her early 40s after a grueling week, utterly drained. Turning the key, she found two of her closest friends in her apartment, a bottle of wine open and takeout containers on the counter. No big questions, just a simple, \"We figured you'd be wiped.\" In that moment, surrounded by the warmth of her chosen family, she felt the deep, structural support she preached about in boardrooms. It taught her that the most resilient and healthy systems are often built on quiet, unconditional empathy.\n\n5.\nJust last fall, on her usual 3.8-mile Muni ride, the idea for her book finally clicked into place. Watching the city\u2019s improbable mix\u2014a cook, a coder, a student\u2014all sharing the same space, she heard her father\u2019s voice talking unions and her mother\u2019s debating classroom dynamics. This bus was a system, a microcosm of the workplaces she advised. In that moment, her entire life synthesized. San Francisco wasn\u2019t just her lab; it was the living embodiment of her work, and she knew exactly what she needed to write."
